  <div class="block block_d right forum_post pinned" data-entry-id="7809742">
  <header>
      <a href="http://www.polygon.com/forums/vita/2015/2/16/8045701/what-would-you-want-for-a-vita-hardware-update#comments" class="comment_count">72 Comments</a>
  </header>

  <div class="pinned_wrapper">
    <div class="block_body">
        <a href="&#x2F;forums&#x2F;vita" class="block_img" data-analytics-link="fanpost:image">
    <q>PlayStation Vita</q>
  </a>

<div class="meta">
  <h2><a href="http:&#x2F;&#x2F;www.polygon.com&#x2F;forums&#x2F;vita&#x2F;2015&#x2F;2&#x2F;16&#x2F;8045701&#x2F;what-would-you-want-for-a-vita-hardware-update" data-analytics-link="fanpost">What would you want from a PlayStation Vita hardware&nbsp;update?</a></h2>
  <p class="byline">
    By <a href="http://www.polygon.com/users/Omnimoak">Omnimoak</a>
    <span class="long_date">

          on Feb 16, 2015
    </span>
    <span class="short_date">
      02.16.15
    </span>
  </p>
  <div class="copy">
  
So it's been three years with the Vita and I think it deserves a hardware change. Here is my list of features and justification of them.

Ditch the rear touchpad, one of the least used features in any game. See point #2
Add physical R2/L2 analog triggers as well as R3/L3 in the thumb sticks. Most ported games use the rear or front touchpad for these buttons anyway, might as well make it comfortable to use. This also has the added affect to make game ports easier. As it will bring the Vita nearly 1:1 to a Dualshock.
Ergonomics, adding analog triggers would make the Vita even more difficult to hold for long periods of time, it's time they embrace the fact they already toe the line on pocketability and just add some grips. 
Battery life, having grips means more space for battery...
</div>

</div>

    </div>
  </div>
</div>
