<div class="meta">
  <h2>
      <a href="http://www.polygon.com/2015/2/17/8049951/citizens-of-earth-review-pc-ps4-playstation-4-wii-u-vita-3ds" data-analytics-link="review">Citizens of Earth review: executive&nbsp;order</a>
  </h2>
  <p class="byline">
      By <a href="http://www.polygon.com/users/pkollar">Philip Kollar</a>
  <span class="long_date">
      on Feb 17, 2015
  </span>
  <span class="short_date">
    02.17.15
  </span>
  <span class="m-entry-admin-button " data-remote-admin-entry-type="button" data-remote-admin-entry-id="7813992"></span>

</p>

  <div class="copy">
  Citizens of Earth shares its greatest strength with many of history's most successful politicians: It's able to appeal to multiple demographics.

In this case, that means a very conservative, old-school role-playing game masked by bright colors and clever writing.¬†Citizens of Earth has its share of grinding. Its slow turn-based combat system requires careful, strategic choices. It has a bevy of design decisions that would normally turn away all but the most hardcore and nostalgic of RPG fans.
Yet Citizens of Earth's cheery disposition is impossible to ignore. It approaches the dustiest of mechanics with a wide-eyed imagination, rethinking them in a way that fits its colorful, goofy world. I went into it feeling a bit of RPG burnout, but Citizens of Earth's enthusiasm won me over in...
</div>

